            <div style="margin-left: 36px; margin-top: 320px; position: relative; width: 928px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_1 shape-with-text flowDefining">
              <div class="text-content style_External_928_1497" style="padding: 0px; ">
                <div class="style">
                  <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1"><br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1">0.5 * 1 - 0.5 * 1 = 0 (in technical terms this is the expected value at any instant)<br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1">Let’s say I rigged the game so that coin toss is somehow manipulated so that probability of heads coming up is 33% and tails coming up is 67%. If I propose the same game like before then it’s not fair. Why?<br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1"><br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1">0.33 * 1 - 0.67 * 1 = _NOT EQUAL_ to zero<br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1">What about this?<br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1">0.33 * (0.5/0.33) + 0.67*(0.5/0.67) * -1 = 0<br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1">The numbers in brackets force the probabilities to 0.5 to make the game fair. Of course it’s just symbol manipulation but that’s what it is!<br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1"><br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1">I can also say p = 0.33 and 1-p =(approx) 0.67<br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1">so p*1+(1-p)(-1) = _NOT EQUAL_ to zero<br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1">1*p*(0.5/p) + (1-p) *(0.5/(1-p))*-1 = 0. These numbers 0.5/p and 0.5/(1-p) are basically loading the probabilities to make them fair. <br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1"><br /></span></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1">In real world the coin might be loaded with 33% /67% probability but in some fair game I change these probabilities. These probabilities which make the cash flow at the end fair to everyone are called risk neutral probabilities. <br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1"><br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1">If this is clear I can actually price a crude derivative with this concept, without any complicated formula. It’s about to expire in let’s say a minute or so. <br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1">Derivative pricing is all about cash flows at maturity or at expiry. To generate these cash flows you have stocks or a single stock (for a single derivative) which you buy or sell in some quantity to replicate it.<br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1">Stock price currently is at 100 and probability of stock going to 101 is 60% and stock going to 99 is 40%. No other scenario is possible and I want to price a 100 strike call. <br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1"><br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1">So for case 1) It reaches 101 - Cash flow is 1<br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1">case 2) It reaches 99 - cash flow is 0<br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1"><br /></span></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_1"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1">Price = 0.5*1+0.5*0 = 0.5. Why 0.5? Coz if I had bought 0.5 quantity of stock at the beginning of 1 minute and sold the call option my portfolio value is <br /></span></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_1"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1"><br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1">Case 1) 1 - 0.5*(101-100) = 0.5<br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1">Case 2) 0 - 0.5*(99-100) = 0.5<br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1"><br /></span></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_2"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1">which is same as option value...and well this is where you have the concept of replicating portfolio. But what about 60% and 40%? Why didn’t I use them. Well they are real world probabilities and I don’t care about them. I forced them to be 50,50 coz otherwise I can’t make this game fair. Yes derivatives trading is a gamble or a game. above example is an extremely simple, but of course by definition <br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1"><br /></span></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_3"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1">Risk Neutral Probability - A probability which eliminates arbitrage when pricing the derivative. Or make the game a fair value game. <br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1"><br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1"><br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1"><br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1"><br /></span></p>
                  <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1"><br /></span></p>
